{"title_page": "Kurdistan National Congress", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Kurdish National Council}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:Kurdish National Congress meeting with PDPKS.png|thumb|Members of the Kurdistan National Congress with [[Kurdish Democratic Progressive Party]] representatives in January 2019.]]\n\nThe '''Kurdistan National Congress''' (Kurdish: ''Kongreya Netewey\u00ee ya Kurdistan\u00ea,'' '''KNC''' or '''KNK''') is a multi-national platform of Kurdish groups and parties of all tendencies, which aims to Independence of Kurdistan. It was founded on 14 April 1985 on the initiative of the [[Kurdistan Workers' Party]]. It was inaugurated on 24 May 1999 in [[Brussels]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Meho|first1=Lokman I.|title=The Kurdish Question in U.S. Foreign Policy: A Documentary Sourcebook|date=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=9780313314353|page=392|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BD7imPDFto0C|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Pojmann|first1=W.|title=Migration and Activism in Europe since 1945|date=2008|publisher=Springer|isbn=9780230615540|page=72|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_e_HAAAAQBAJ|language=en}}</ref>\nThe group has more recently be referred to as the Kurdistan National Congress in the Diaspora.<ref>{{cite web|title=What kind of peace? The case of the Turkish and Kurdish peace process|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/latif-tas/what-kind-of-peace-case-of-turkish-and-kurdish-peace-process|website=openDemocracy|language=en|date=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe convention of the KNC was endorsed on 26 May 1999, at the organization's founding assembly, and the scholar [[Ismet Cheriff Vanly]] was declared the first president.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gunter|first1=Michael M.|title=Historical Dictionary of the Kurds|date=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810875074|page=180|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DoNSXwb8D9EC|language=en}}</ref> The convention was amended most recently at the ninth assembly which took place in December 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Convention, Kurdistan National Congress|url=http://www.kongrakurdistan.net:80/en/convention/|publisher=Kurdistan National Congress|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624235212/http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/convention/|archivedate=24 June 2016|date=24 June 2016|access-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRecently conferences held by the group have reaffirmed their wish that [[Kurds]] may have their national identity recognized and the territory of [[Kurdistan]] to be respected.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carment|first1=David|last2=Sadjed|first2=Ariane|title=Diaspora as Cultures of Cooperation: Global and Local Perspectives|date=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319328928|page=189|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9g7_DQAAQBAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe congress is constituted by 288 members for the term from October 2017 to October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/members/|title=Members {{!}} Kurdistan National Congress|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>  \n\nPresident of the KNC until at least 1999 was [[Najmaldin Karim]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Farkas|first1=E.|title=Fractured States and U.S. Foreign Policy: Iraq, Ethiopia, and Bosnia in the 1990s|date=2003|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781403982438|page=153|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hjXIAAAAQBAJ|language=en}}</ref> Two co-chairs of the KNK, Rebwar Rashed and Nil\u00fcfer Ko\u00e7 were elected to post on 27 September 2015 at the 15th General Meeting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Co-President|url=http://www.kongrakurdistan.net:80/en/co-president/|publisher=Kurdistan National Congress|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624233529/http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/co-president/|archivedate=24 June 2016|access-date=25 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Both were re-elected on 15 October 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/co-president/|title=Co-President {{!}} Kurdistan National Congress|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> \n\n== Criticism ==\nKurdish affairs expert [[Michael Gunter]] reckoned that the KNC has had difficulty attracting wide participation from Kurdish people, and has appeared to be too close to the [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] (PKK).<ref name=\"Gunter\">{{cite book|last1=Gunter|first1=Michael M.|author-link=Michael Gunter |title=Historical Dictionary of the Kurds|date=2018|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781538110508|page=198|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i7hJDwAAQBAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Weblinks ==\n[http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/welcome/ Official Webpage]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kurdish organisations}}\n{{Poli-stub}}\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Kurdish organisations]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political party alliances]]\n[[Category:Kurdistan Workers' Party]]\n[[Category:Political party alliances in Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Kurdish National Council}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:Kurdish National Congress meeting with PDPKS.png|thumb|Members of the Kurdistan National Congress with [[Kurdish Democratic Progressive Party]] representatives in January 2019.]]\n\nThe '''Kurdistan National Congress''' (Kurdish: ''Kongreya Netewey\u00ee ya Kurdistan\u00ea,'' '''KNC''' or '''KNK''') is a multi-national platform of kurdish groups and parties of all tendencies, which aims to Independence of Kurdistan. It was founded on 14 April 1985 on the initiative of the [[Kurdistan Workers' Party]]. It was inaugurated on 24 May 1999 in [[Brussels]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Meho|first1=Lokman I.|title=The Kurdish Question in U.S. Foreign Policy: A Documentary Sourcebook|date=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=9780313314353|page=392|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BD7imPDFto0C|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Pojmann|first1=W.|title=Migration and Activism in Europe since 1945|date=2008|publisher=Springer|isbn=9780230615540|page=72|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_e_HAAAAQBAJ|language=en}}</ref>\nThe group has more recently be referred to as the Kurdistan National Congress in the Diaspora.<ref>{{cite web|title=What kind of peace? The case of the Turkish and Kurdish peace process|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/latif-tas/what-kind-of-peace-case-of-turkish-and-kurdish-peace-process|website=openDemocracy|language=en|date=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe convention of the KNC was endorsed on 26 May 1999, at the organization's founding assembly, and the scholar [[Ismet Cheriff Vanly]] was declared the first president.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gunter|first1=Michael M.|title=Historical Dictionary of the Kurds|date=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810875074|page=180|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DoNSXwb8D9EC|language=en}}</ref> The convention was amended most recently at the ninth assembly which took place in December 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Convention, Kurdistan National Congress|url=http://www.kongrakurdistan.net:80/en/convention/|publisher=Kurdistan National Congress|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624235212/http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/convention/|archivedate=24 June 2016|date=24 June 2016|access-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRecently conferences held by the group have reaffirmed their wish that [[Kurds]] may have their national identity recognized and the territory of [[Kurdistan]] to be respected.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carment|first1=David|last2=Sadjed|first2=Ariane|title=Diaspora as Cultures of Cooperation: Global and Local Perspectives|date=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319328928|page=189|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9g7_DQAAQBAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe congress is constituted by 288 members for the term from October 2017 to October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/members/|title=Members {{!}} Kurdistan National Congress|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>  \n\nPresident of the KNC until at least 1999 was [[Najmaldin Karim]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Farkas|first1=E.|title=Fractured States and U.S. Foreign Policy: Iraq, Ethiopia, and Bosnia in the 1990s|date=2003|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781403982438|page=153|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hjXIAAAAQBAJ|language=en}}</ref> Two co-chairs of the KNK, Rebwar Rashed and Nil\u00fcfer Ko\u00e7 were elected to post on 27 September 2015 at the 15th General Meeting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Co-President|url=http://www.kongrakurdistan.net:80/en/co-president/|publisher=Kurdistan National Congress|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624233529/http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/co-president/|archivedate=24 June 2016|access-date=25 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Both were re-elected on 15 October 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/co-president/|title=Co-President {{!}} Kurdistan National Congress|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> \n\n== Criticism ==\nKurdish affairs expert [[Michael Gunter]] reckoned that the KNC has had difficulty attracting wide participation from Kurdish people, and has appeared to be too close to the [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] (PKK).<ref name=\"Gunter\">{{cite book|last1=Gunter|first1=Michael M.|author-link=Michael Gunter |title=Historical Dictionary of the Kurds|date=2018|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781538110508|page=198|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i7hJDwAAQBAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Weblinks ==\n[http://www.kongrakurdistan.net/en/welcome/ Official Webpage]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kurdish organisations}}\n{{Poli-stub}}\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Kurdish organisations]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political party alliances]]\n[[Category:Kurdistan Workers' Party]]\n[[Category:Political party alliances in Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: kurdish \u2192 Kurdish", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org